text:
-content warning: sexual assault-
there are things that remain
i long to release 
but every time i stir them up in my mind
words refuse to exit my mouth 
if i allow my consciousness to descend 
into the cavern where those truths reside
stepping down each rung with a caution
a weightlessness i grew accustomed to
sacrificing my voice 
ensuring the darkness i hid in 
remained in tact
landmines buried to keep me in line 
you joked youâ€™d never hit me
because i was bigger than you
the way youâ€™d be certain to say with a smile
â€œi want to shake youâ€
â€œi left so i wouldnâ€™t hit youâ€
as though i should be grateful 
for such restraint 
you never laid your hands on me 
at least not in the daylight 
not in the ways that one could point to
when nothing felt right 
your words beat me instead 
battered down
bloody 
cement poured down my throat
setting in my every joint
making it easier each time to ignore
my words
calling me a tease
when all i did was breathe
existing each moment
cautious with every movement so 
as to not unintentionally entice 
shut myself in that tiny bathroom
pieces of me falling off
sobbing in silence 
aching
bleeding 
while 20 feet away you rested peacefully 
are you even aware of what you did to me?
all this time later
i still canâ€™t call it what it was

a piece of me still sits in that darkness
hidden away for fear of what those i 
love will say 
the day that shadow i left inside
breaks away 
aches too deeply for the light 
to stay left behind
â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”i have to admit, this isnâ€™t the first poem iâ€™ve written about this experience, but it is by far the most transparent, and posting it was not a decision that i took lightly. i have felt a tug at my heart as i continue in this journey of healing, to be more willing to be open. to allow the light i have within me to be made a beacon for others, so that anyone who interacts with myself or my work will walk away knowing they are not alone. i just want you to know that no matter what you are going through, you are never alone and you will get through this. i know there are days it doesnâ€™t feel this way. seven months have passed and there are still days where i canâ€™t see past it, but i will. ğŸ’–ğŸ¦‹ #metoo

text: as we move forward, the paint i'm mixing is setting, coag-yalating, goop. things that may help for futureness, success, keeping growth in our communities. i don't smoke weed. if you think my panic attacks are bad sober, you for sure don't want to see any type of dabbling with that. i'll be hiding in the dark, crying, taping my feet to the floor.  i'm little, malnourished, it attacks fatty tissues and cells and those are all in my brain. anywho, investing in medical marijuana, that industry isn't going anywhere, set those kids up for a future! p.s. as much as i miss home sometimes, not today, dodging those subzero temps of -30 , -50 with windchill. stay alive friends! #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #dabuisness #shutdownstories

text:
mental health, itâ€™s such a heavy subject, but a very important one. one that unfortunately has a lot of stigma around it therefore preventing people from opening up about their own mental well-being, including myself. iâ€™ll never forget the first time i went to the doctor after struggling to cope with sexual abuse trauma and being diagnosed as having post traumatic stress disorder and depression. never did i think i would fit the definition, i thought i was resilient and could handle anything. despite having a perfectly good reason to feel as i did, i was embarrassed and told very few people that not only was i on anti-depressants but also seeing a psychologist. my embarrassment came from the stigma around mental health illness. and as you can imagine, 13 years ago, there was even more than exists today. for the longest time, i hardly spoke of any of my mental health issues and worked very hard to overcome them or at least disguise them. as i reflected on my diagnosis over the years, i recalled something that my physician told me when he diagnosed me. he had actually shared his own personal struggles with mental illness and because he did not hide it, that somehow gave me a bit more confidence to open up and start talking. with movements like the #metoo and #ibelieveyou campaign, i have become even more confident in opening up about my trauma and mental health issues that stem from it. iâ€™m no longer embarrassed and am proud of myself for embracing vulnerability. i truly believe that if we continue to talk about our mental well-being, we will begin to heal and become more empathic and understanding of one another. #bellletstalk is yet another great campaign that is raising awareness about such an important topic and am hopeful it resonates with many and that the positive impact continues and not forgotten about at the end of the day. talking about mental health is scary as fuck, but so rewarding. if youâ€™d like to talk, reach out. reach out to family, friends, all the incredible resources available and to me! i may not always know what to say, but i can listen, share and offer hugs. hugs are my favourite. ğŸ¤— .
.
#stopthestigma

today i was asked what does #advocacy look like in the eyes of a survivor. 
advocacy for me is going into the environments where voices of victims have been silenced and offering a stage for them to be seen and heard.  a sacred space that encourages vulnerability as strength and not for hurting. advocacy is more than an act of â€œshowing upâ€ it is a launching point of â€œshowing out.â€ an opportunity for victims and survivors to exercise their voice and heal through community.

@rarcc_support  has offered that for me and continues to offer that to me. 
if you are hesitant to begin your healing journey.... all i can give is what you see here. a gal who was just as timid as you who took a 2 year journey of healing & here she is today. facing all her fears & growing with a community. .

text:
many know i've have struggled with mental health throughout the years from insomnia, major depressive disorder, social and generalized anxiety, to spending 3 months in the alberta children and foothills hospitals for bulimia. 
this past year and 6 months i've been dealing with something new that i never thought possible for someone to get at only 20, post traumatic stress disorder. i'm continuing to learn how to manage my life with this illness, ptsd, but i am incredibly grateful to my boyfriend as well as my long distance friends in calgary who are there for me to talk to and support me. you are not alone. if you ever need someone to talk to, i am always here to listen. #bellletstalk #mentalhealthawareness #metoo

text:
it took me a year after the last assault to tell my parents what had happened. i never thought i would tell them, but hiding it from the people i love was hurting me more than keeping me sane.  i don't regret telling them, and i would love to be able to tell all of the people i care for about this part of my life. but i can't. i'm so afraid that they will look at me like i'm broken, that i will never be the same in their eyes again. so i don't. all i say is i love you and i'm sorry. 
if you have any suggestions or stories about how to open up to loved ones, i would love to hear them!

text:
i never thought of myself as a person who needed to speak truth to my soul. things like â€œyouâ€™re beautifulâ€ â€œyouâ€™re smartâ€ â€œyou have people who are on your sideâ€, standing in front of a mirror looking at myself in all my imperfectious glory. forcing my eyes to see something good. 
a thought entered my mind today. it was automatic. it didnâ€™t even stutter as it filled my headspace with what i consistently have to convince myself as falsehoods. 
i closed my eyes, smiled and literally said out loud â€œ wow, jamee where did that even come fromâ€  rhetorical question really, as i can think of a million reasons why i would come up with such pernicious notions. 
i didnâ€™t always stop and question my thoughts. i deserved to feel the way they made me feel. 
but today i did. it made me realize how much i need to tell myself â€œi am worthy of loveâ€ and so many other truths that need to pour out of my mouth and into my ears.  #healing #survivor #abusesurvivor #journey #bloggers #selfdiscovery #timesup #stillirise #breakthesilence #selflove #jamisonsjourney #empower #trauma #support #awareness #survivorsunite #supportgroup #metoo #1in4girls

on monday, february 4th at 8pm, one year to the day of her world premiere, kamakshi hart will perform her award-winning one-woman show "wild at hart".â €
.â €
in wild at hart, kamakshi hart vividly tells her story of how she found the ways to survive, heal and rise above traumatic events that began in early childhood. aligning with today's redefining social initiatives, such as #metoo and #timesup, kamakshi shares her story to initiate enlightened conversations that will stimulate real cultural change and transformation. through her courageous narrative, kamakshi illuminates the value of telling our stories and the grace of healing that comes when we are truly heard.  her show is for mid-teens and up. if bringing your teen, please be with them and be prepared for a frank and open conversation with them about the subject matter.â €
.â €

text:
the #faxx are in: itâ€™s now 2019 and leading public health scholars still tend to downplay the potential effects of political determinants such as gender politics on population health, so these study authors looked for, found and recorded actual correlations between the numbers of women in government and population health outcomes. why it matters: gender politics matters in public health because it helps to determine â€œwho gets what, when and how.â€ the study determined that female politicians hold more liberal attitudes with regard to issues like civil rights and egalitarianism; and promote the types of spending predictive of lower mortality rates, for example, like preventive care, and social services. research also shown that women in government tend to work in more collaborative and bipartisan ways, employ a more democratic leadership style, are more effective at building coalitions and reaching consensus. what to do: get more women into politics, and support the initiatives of the women who are already there. call your senator our county representative and see if they have any health or other initiatives you can support.

text:
this is a tough picture for me to share but this is what a victim of abuse looks like. i look starved but i ate every day. that's just weight loss from stress. my eyes were bloodshot. my hair was falling out. it had probably been 5 days since i've showered when this photo was taken. i was miserable, depressed, and i felt trapped. when this photo was taken, he was taking me out to lunch. he paid for both of our meals. he never let me spend a dime of my own in a way that seemed like he was taking care of me on the outside but on the inside it was his way of forcing me to rely on him. some people think that talking about the abuse is me trying to attack an innocent man. this photo is evidence against that. i've dated assholes since but never in my life had i looked worse due to deteriorated mental health. look at this photo and compare it to other photos i've posted online. you can tell something's wrong with me here. it's been just over 4 years of healing from him now and i've come a long way. #survivor #survivorstories #metoo #abuse #emotionalabuse #abusiverelationship #mentalhealthawareness #stopvictimblaming 
for the record i post things like this every now and then because i want to open up about my story and then 5 minutes after posting it i take it down because i get very anxious because opening up publicly about it is scary. chances are this won't be up long.
name: Amy Splitz
tweet_full:
this is a tough picture for me to share but this is what a victim of abuse looks like. i look starved but i ate every day. that's just weight loss from stress. my eyes were bloodshot. my hair was falling out. it had probably been 5 days since i have showered when this photo was taken. i was miserable, depressed, and i felt trapped. when this photo was taken, he was taking me out to lunch. he paid for both of our meals. he never let me spend a dime of my own in a way that seemed like he was taking care of me on the outside but on the inside it was his way of forcing me to rely on him. some people think that talking about the abuse is me trying to attack an innocent man. this photo is evidence against that. i have dated assholes since but never in my life had i looked worse due to deteriorated mental health. look at this photo and compare it to other photos i have posted online. you can tell something's wrong with me here. it is been just over 4 years of healing from him now and i have come a long way. #survivor #survivorstories #metoo #abuse #emotionalabuse #abusiverelationship #mentalhealthawareness #stopvictimblaming 
for the record i post things like this every now and then because i want to open up about my story and then 5 minutes after posting it i take it down because i get very anxious because opening up publicly about it is scary. chances are this will not be up long.

text: so for #bellletstalk day i decided that i wanted to bring up a very stigmatized issue and an issue that has effected my mental heath in a very serious way. on december 8th 2018 i was sexually assaulted. i had been asleep after a night of drinking with friends when i woke up to a familiar boy taking advantage of me. i couldnâ€™t move or speak, i was paralyzed with fear. i had bruises from how aggressively i was grabbed. when i got home, i sat in the bath for 3 and a half hours because i couldnâ€™t shake the feeling of absolute disgust. i couldnâ€™t sleep for 3 days after the assault and i had panic attacks multiple times a day because of the seemingly little things that triggered me. i have flashbacks multiple times a day and have panic attacks. not many people know this about me as it is a very vulnerable thing for me to share and iâ€™m very concerned that by posting this there will be people talking about me and my situation. but iâ€™ve come to realize recently, that i should not be the one ashamed because i was sexually assaulted, the boy who did this to me should. and yet as i type this with the hopes that i am brave enough to post this, my heart is racing at the thought of being talked about as â€œthat girlâ€ or being victim blamed or shamed. the situation i went through almost two months ago has affected me in the worst ways possible and has changed my attitude, my outlook on society and my mental health tremendously. i am so terrified to share my story but i want other girls that have gone through the same trauma to know that no matter what it is not your fault and that you should never feel ashamed for what happened to you as easy as it is to just blame yourself. if any girl in a similar position ever needs to talk or just wants someone who can understand how they are feeling i am always here, no matter what! 1 in 3 women are affected by sexual violence and yet there is still such a huge stigma and girls are still victim blamed! de- stigmatize sexual assault victims and mental illness surrounding the issue! #metoo #bellletstalk

â€œas much as we try to believe that hate and evil of this nature no longer exists thereâ€™s always a moment like this that threatens to make our heart sick. and so we choose to do the opposite of what their terror suggests and bind together with love, compassion, and prayer because it is the only things potent enough to eradicate hate. 
_
the terror inflicted on @jussiesmollett and all others whoâ€™ve been triggered by this news is reprehensible. tonight iâ€™m praying that he and so many others will feel the love of millions slicing through the pain. 
_
if youâ€™re reading this and youâ€™re especially afraid because youâ€™ve seen similar days hear me from the depths of my heart when i say: your life matters. you are seen. you are loved. this world can be scary, but i know of a perfect love that casts out fear. iâ€™m praying this serves as a reminder that god hears and sees you. 
_
may we all love a little bit louder and wiser until hate is afraid to rear its ugly head.â€ -sarah jakes roberts

european parliamentâ€™s #metoo measure â€˜incredibly stupid,â€™ says german mep â€“ politico
#
german mep hans-olaf henkel | carsten koall/getty images german mep hans-olaf henkel, vice-chair of the european conservatives and reformists, has accused leaders of other groups in the european parliament of being "removed from realityâ€œ for backing plans to bar meps from key posts if they don't sign up to anti-harassment commitments and training. the mooted measure, in an amendmentÂ to a planned revisionÂ of parliamentâ€™s rules of procedure, is seen as a way to reassure european citizens that their assembly treats harassment seriously, ahead of the may election and as the #metoo campaign continues to resonate. someÂ german conservative meps have been criticizedÂ for resisting the plans. in a letter to all meps wednesday, the leaders of several political alliances â€” including udo bullmann of the progressive alliance of socialists and democrats, guy verhofstadt of the alliance of liberals and democrats for europe, and philippe lamberts of the greens and european free alliance â€” urged them toÂ vote for the #metoo measures on thursday, sayingÂ it was time "to show our real commitment and ambition before electing a new european parliament." henkel, an independent mep, dashed off an email reply â€” seen by politico â€” saying bluntly: "have you all become crazy? how about preventing stealing,â€¦

text:
not only is it very rare that a survivor comes forward with their story, but traumatic. they risk their sense of belonging. they risk being scrutinized for the ways they do not present as the â€œperfect survivor.â€ this gets further complicated for trans, queer, and students of color & many men who are told by our culture that they canâ€™t be seen as a victim of assault. the difference between a student filing a title ix complaint and reporting to law enforcement is that title ix is a policy designed around maintaining a safe educational space free of discrimination based on sex while the criminal justice system is an actor of the state and is meant to determine if the person found guilty of a crime should loose their total freedom. this is not what title ix does. the most severe consequence from the process is expulsion which students experience far more frequently for instances of cheating or plagiarism. 
being assaulted by another student creates a very toxic educational space. this is what title ix is meant to protect against from k-12 and throughout higher education. but all too often when a student makes the painful choice to come forward and seek protections from their school, administrators, peers, and members of the public view them as an adversary of the university and disproportionately protect the assailant, who oftentimes has more connections to money and power and is more likely to sue. mishandling title ix complaints is a violation of civil rights. advocates have fought for years to advance federal regulations to help move universities towards better practices. 
@betsydevosed and her proposed changes to the policy is a huge step backwards and perpetuates the narrative that the assailant and the bloated institution of the university is the one who needs protection. we ask for a more compassionate response and a larger imagination for the possibilities of campus culture. 
you can support the integrity of the title ix process in 3 ways that we outline when you swipe left after watching abbeyâ€™s testimony. letâ€™s do this!
â€”â€”â€”â€”
#titleix #ocr #whatweknowfilm #betsydevos #indiefilm #womeninfilm #survivor #healing #metoo #timesup #whyididntreport

text:
how do you prevent bullying?
employers have a duty of care to their people so a commitment to tackling workplace bullying is paramount, whatever the seniority of the perpetrator, whatever the value of the client â€“ after all, do you really want your organisation associated with these types of individuals?
this commitment also needs to be made publicly to your people and accessible to them. victims will be encouraged (and perpetrators discouraged) by being made aware of their rights and what to do if they are bullied in your workplace. itâ€™s knowledge that is power, not the humiliation and intimidation of others, so give people the tools to tackle bullying.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
i was lucky enough to have had front row tickets to a tour of @facebook in #siliconvalley. the tour was given by none other than nicola mendelsohn @nicolamen herself. head of #facebook #europe, pioneering #womenempowerment #entrepreneurship,  #shemeansbusiness and #femalefounders as part of the facebook #diversity initiative.

as part of the 2015 queen of englands' birthday honours, nicola received a commander of the order of the british empire (#cbe) for services to the creative industries. she was also named one of most influential #womenintech, is a wife, mother and fighting cancer. 
having met nicola, i found her very direct when talking #business, yet incredibly soft hearted as a person. no matter who you are, i think you'll agree we can all learn something from a #kickasswoman like her!

text:
"feminism and popcorn!", a great series of events combining feminist movie nights, interesting panel discussions and networking while eating popcorn, created by @fesonline.
***
i attended my first fap-event tonight, learned new things (example: did you know that women in switzerland only gained the right to vote in federal elections in 1971?) or deepend existing knowledge: "die freiheitskÃ¤mpfe der frauen - 100 jahre frauenwahlrecht" is a documentary from 2018. although it has its focus on 100 years of female suffrage in germany (which we celebrated last year) it also includes topics like #metoo, the right for abortion or the necessity of parity and quota for women in politics and media. in only 45 minutes the documentary also managed to pick up the fight for women's rights worldwide. well done!
***
the cherry on the cake: directors sabine jainski and ilona kalmbach were there tonight to talk about their work (besides three other inspiring women from politics and media who also participated in the panel discussion). looking forward to the next fep-event!
***
ps: of course, i kept my popcorn bag that you can see on the right side :-)
***

text:
several years ago it took courage for me to appear in court for the mother of a client who had alleged having been physically abused by her young daughter's biological father. the court battle was to decide whether the father should be entitled to unsupervised visitation with his daughter, my client, who at the time was around the age of 6. my intention was to inform the court of how it is that violence against a pregnant mother can have a damaging impact on the unborn fetus. this was relevant because during the time of the abuse, the mother was pregnant with my client. 
it took particular courage because the father had somehow secured my personal information, such as private home phone number and home address. the history had revealed that this was an aggressive man who did not want his efforts to obtain unsupervised visits with his daughter interfered with. there was also some evidence that he had sexually molested his daughter (my client) when she was at or under the age of 4.

in spite of his history, i made the decision that i had no choice but to tell the judge and the court what i knew about the potential emotional and psychological damage he could do to my client and her mother. because of that, i strongly argued in court against allowing unsupervised visits between her and her dad. 
#1000actsofcourage
#thischangeseverything
#illuminatefilmfestival

#womensreality #metoo #everydaysexism #fem2 #feminism#feminist #actofcourage

text: hearing @caelynnmillerkeyes story on the bachelor this week brought back so many emotions and memories of my experience with sexual assault. it breaks my heart seeing so many amazing, strong, smart, successful, beautiful women go through such a horrific thing. every 98 seconds an american is sexually assaulted, and every 11 minutes that victim is a child. no one should ever have to deal with that and it absolutely infuriates me that people think they can take advantage of another human being. sharing my experience is really difficult and itâ€™s terrifying to open up about something that i was so ashamed of for so long, but the only way to stop this epidemic is to talk about it. i felt guilty, dirty, and so ashamed that i didnâ€™t want my family or friends to know what happened to me. no one deserves that. no one deserves to lose control over their body. stories like caelynnâ€™s keep me inspired to continue to share my story in hopes of helping other women feel empowered and know they are not alone. so here i am with a smile on my face showing him that he doesnâ€™t get to take one more second of my happiness from me! @rainn @itsonus #metoo #stopthesilence

text:
as you know, i had the honor to be invited to speak at @ucla this past weekend. as a proud alumni of @ucla_engineering , i came back to discuss my experience in the engineering world and how i define leadership, resilience and combat gender issues. i've had all sorts of experiences, from harrassment to a huge pay gap because i was a woman, to being yelled at for having a brain, and all sorts of other challenges. some made me cry, some made me scared, but all of them developed my backbone into steel. 
here are a couple of videos i was lucky to have someone from the audience share with me! have you experienced gender inequality? this goes to both men and women!

text: today is #bellletstalk day. today is also a week since the man who tried to kill me was released from jail. the last 3 years of my life have not been easy. in june of 2016 i met a man, a man who i started dating. i thought this man was the love of my life. in the beginning he treated me amazing, he literally swept me off of my feet. he would clean, do my laundry, surprise me with meaningful gifts, and so much more. now i realize he did those things only to make it seem like he was the perfect boyfriend. the signs of abuse started early on but easily went over my head. see in the beginning the abuse was mental, it didnâ€™t become physical until later. i became so manipulated and convinced that i was meant to be with this man; i saw the good in him and i believed that he was a good person.. he wasnâ€™t, he isnâ€™t, i donâ€™t think he ever will be. when this man first started physically abusing me i was shocked and confused. i couldnâ€™t understand why the person i loved, the person who supposedly loved me could hurt me like that. my mind went a million directions, but my heart told me i loved him. in the back of my head i always knew that it wasnâ€™t ok but my love for him masked it. i tried to protect him, our relationship. i did what i could to make sure no one knew what he was doing to me. see i didnâ€™t even have to tell anyone he was abusing me, they all figured it out. but i kept trying to hide it, i would make up excuses and lies to protect him. i became isolated from my friends and family. he manipulated me in so many ways. i was convinced to leave school and move in with him. i never spoke to my friends or family. my abuser didnâ€™t only hit me, he choked me. he always went to choking me. imagine the person you love choking you every day. spewing hate into your mind and body every day. when you wake up in the morning you donâ€™t know if it will be a good day or a bad day. scared of what to say, where to look, what to wear. imagine the person you love telling you he is going to kill you. thinking you will never see your family again.. being choked so bad that you black out. but you wake up again. you escape. you run. you survive. #metoo #survivor #domesticviolence

text:
my name is vanessa mÃ¼nstermann
.
i was born in 1989, i have been living a normal life as a child and adolescents, with the exception of my type 1 diabetes. i have an advanced high school certificate, i am a trained beautician and worked at my parents' filling station. in 2015 a man crossed my path, daniel. "he is my destiny", i thought to myself
.
with time, he began to act strange. he is aggressive one minute and the next, he is weeping like a child. heâ€™s a beautiful man, if i hadn't been captivated by his looks, i would have had to see much sooner that he is totally crazy
.
eventually, i separated from him. in february 2016, early in the morning,he poured acid on my face. everything happened so very fast. he came at me out of the bushes, i had no chance to run away. a woman heard my scream and hastened to help. â€œdo not touch me,â€ i told her instinctively, spitting out the acid. i fainted in the hospital car
.
i was put in an induced coma for twelve days. i was pumped with morphine. i had 20 operations. one ear is missing, one eye is almost completely destroyed, my mouth hanging obliquely. my face, hands, and dÃ©colletÃ© are littered with scars. and that will remain so
.
i decided to keep the scars
.
i will not hide
.
daniel tried to destroy me. but he has destroyed himself.he was sentenced to 12 years imprisonment in 2016
.
countless people helped me and thought of me and were there for me, for which i am indefinitely grateful. now i want to help other people. and think of them. and be there for them
.
it does not matter if we are disfigured by an acid attack, a fire, an accident or from birth, we are different. we are unique. we are excellent
.
we have been hurt. the scars remain. but we will not break
.
and for that we must be visible. go outside. show us the world
.
i wish that sometime soon, i'll find a partner who accepts me as i am, maybe start a family, as difficult as that sounds with me â€“ that would be nice!
.
i'm vanessa mÃ¼nstermann. i am disfigured, but not broken!
.
via: diaryofanaijagirl

text: do not imagine it possible to know another's mind... even if it lay open to be read by passerby. thoughts are divinely individual, nuanced with experience and pain. passions, whether hate or love dance in a tainted rain the out-sider is not able to see, let alone smell or taste. every synapse individual...even within the same brain...so do not imagine you...the bystander...as having a knowing even when the story is thrown your feet.

p r o g r e ss +  r e f l e c t i o n |  my wellness journey is a lot about these two things; not only physically but also mentally. especially because of the close-knit links anxiety has to them.

january has been such a good month, albeit stressful at times but nothing we haven't or couldn't overcome. i started dietbet as a way to kickstart the year with an intention of working out a lot. that lasted about a week before my main focus went onto to kai & eating habits.

not only have these changes â¬† my energy levels, they've also lowered my anxiety levels & my water retention. combined with food inspo'd by @chefpeteevans
paleo way & prolonged fasting periods, i won #jordanshrinksdietbet weighing in the month at a whooping 90.2kg and weighing out of january at 85.3kg

text:
i have learnt my feminism from the sex workers who have taught me to not read power in absolutist terms and to not take power too seriously. many decades before #metoo the sex workers at sonagachi had mobilised against sexual harassment, police atrocities and state violations, and formed their own union. clearly the current public sphere around gender should learn a thing or two from the sex workers movement which refuses to invest and read power in the figure of the oppressor, rather locates the site of sex as that which undoes and inverts the relations of power. bharati di, the present secretary of dmsc ardently told me last year that sex work is the only profession that doesn't discriminate on grounds of religion, caste or class - "whoever comes to us leaves with joy, happiness, and orgasm" she had said fondly. i kept thinking about this whenever in conversations around #metoo idiots have said that consent cannot be affirmative between two individuals of different power equations, as if a state of absolute power equilibrium is ever possible. had this been the case then ambedkar would not have proposed exogamy as a way of combating patriarchy: sex here is means of an irreverence, a mockery, and a negative force that subtracts power from the powerful. no wonder the greatest critics of dworkin and mackinnon were the sex workers!
*

text: |pleasure| â€œwhen the harvey weinstein stuff started to come out and #metoo picked up steam and then of course uma thurman made her statement against harvey and quentin, i still felt like quentin was a weirdo, certainly, and very particular, maybe even a bit creepy, but not a bad dude. plus, i loved his movies! i was horrified by his spitting on actresses and choking them himself for shots, but thought his response was thoughtful, and listen! all for the art, right man? but a few days later, i read an article on jezebel, which had dug up his howard stern interview from 2003 where he defends roman polanskiâ€™s drugging and raping of a thirteen-year-old girl. i was illâ€”actually illâ€” listening to it. this was ingrained misogynistic behavior, something he believed in deeply. that a thirteen-year-old girl â€˜wanted to have it,â€™ as he laughed and made light of child rape. even howard stern, the original shock jock, seemed shocked. my daughter is ten. i know thirteen-year-olds. i couldnâ€™t help it. i took to twitter, angrily, as we all do nowadays, and fired off a series of tweets condemning him and his stupid art and anyone whoever works with him. fuck that guy. you donâ€™t get to exist in this world anymore, dude. but then he did issue an apology for that interview, which i guess is all he could do. and so he gets to exist for a little while longer, i guess. his movie about the manson murders is about to be filmed. with brad pitt and margot robbie and other stars. iâ€™m sure itâ€™ll be mesmerizing. probably a hit. iâ€™ll skip itâ€ (231). #busyphillips #thiswillonlyhurtalittle #memoir #bookstagram #bookreview #victorianhouse #ireadthisinoneday #welllikeonenight #ijustcouldntputitdown

text:
@howardbrownhealth content disclosure: hate crime, racism, homophobia
.
.
.
.
.
last night, jussie smollett was the target of a hate crime here in chicago. this attack was perpetrated by multiple assailants who hurled violent racist and homophobic slurs at him as they poured a chemical â€“ possibly bleach â€“ on him and tied a rope around his neck.
at howard brown health, from #metoo to #muterkelly to this very moment, we believe survivors and value their words.
hate crimes like this are not one-off occurrences. years of microaggressions, documented difficulty and reticence in charging hate crimes, and the historical devaluation of queer black people have laid the foundation upon which violence like this is built. this attack was not because jussie smollett is gay or is black â€“ it was because he is both gay and black. this extreme violence was perpetrated on the grounds of both race and sexual orientation and tragically illustrates the very real multiple jeopardy that queer and trans people of color face. we can never separate our identities as people of color and queer. 
howard brown stands in support of jussie smollett. his work as an actor, singer, and vocal advocate for both the lgbtq+ community and people living with hiv has inspired our community time and again. in march of 2017, jussie, along with his empire co-star taraji p. henson, visited our young clients at broadway youth center. he inspired us to stay true to what we believe in and uplifted our spirits. now, it is our turn to uplift and advocate for him. 
though our community regularly faces disproportionate levels of violence, acts like this are still painful, damaging, and disturbing. we often reach out, check in, and speak up because we feel a direct connection to what is happening. in moments like this, one of the most validating and supportive things we can do for each other is to honor and center the person who is harmed, including following their lead on what resources they need.
for more information about howard brownâ€™s mental wellness services, please call 773.388.1600 or go to howardbrown.org for more information.

text:
saw the play, "gloria: a life", about the woman who was instrumental in revolutionizing the women's liberation movement, gloria steinem. she, along with many others, fought for a woman's right to equal social standing, equal pay and the dissolution of the idea that womens only place in society is at home watching the kids and in the kitchen. while the fight continues on with movements like #metoo, we can be proud to know that it is because of our mothers, grandmothers and every other woman that came before us, that
women in this country today have reached heights that only a few years ago were just pipedreams. #womensliberation #gloriasteinem #equalrights #gloriaalife
name: Alison Michele Cortes

text:
see you this friday for rosemary meza-desplas: jane anger opening reception 7-9pm! .
pictured here: â€œslow burnâ€
hand sewn human hair. 
amos eno gallery is pleased to present jane anger, an exhibition of new works by rosemary meza-desplas. jane anger features hand-sewn human hair drawings, watercolors and onsite installations. rosemary meza-desplasâ€™ figurative artworks emphasize line and movement. the title refers to a 16th century pamphlet published in england titled jane anger, her protection for women. an opening reception will be held on friday, february 1 from 7-9 pm at the galleryâ€™s location at 56 bogart street in brooklyn, ny. 
meza-desplas, also a spoken word performer, will present her piece titled intervals of anger at the opening reception. she will perform a poem every fifteen minutes in conjunction with an artwork in the exhibition. 
meza-desplas explores the concept of anger as a tool for change by juxtaposing found imagery from social media, art history and mass media. she is interested in how the social movements, womenâ€™s marches and #metoo, harnessed anger in order to forefront an array of gender-based burdens. 
this exhibition includes meza-desplasâ€™ most recent drawings which incorporate her gray hair. she has been sewing with her own hair since 2000. her hair is hand-sewn into a variety of grounds with small embroidery needles. meza-desplasâ€™ decision to collect, sort and utilize hair as a vehicle for art-making is informed by socio-cultural symbolism, feminism and body issues, and religious symbolism. hair embodies a dichotomy: it can be sexy and engaging to people, on the other hand, it can be repulsive â€“ like a hair in your soup or a hair on your hotel pillow. there are religious connotations to hair which coincide with symbolism reflecting strength, sensuality and reverence; such as delila cutting off samsonâ€™s hair and mary magdalen washing the feet of jesus with her hair. .
#hair #hairart #feministart #sewnart #handsewndrawing #amosenogallery #rosemarymezadesplas

please join me in making a comment at handsoffix.org before midnight tonight; as a survivor, title ix offered me safety, reassurance, and options for actions to take against my assaulter. yes, it has its faulty moments, but ultimately itâ€™s the only way universities are able to help the victims of sexual assaults on campus. if the new legislation passes, itâ€™ll enable the schools to cover up sexual assault cases.

â€¢â£
survivors like caelynn remind us that there is a light after all that darkness. â€œit weakens you. it really does. it was the darkest time in my life,â€ she said, speaking about her experience. but she continued, going on about how she has been able to continue with her recovery. â€œmy focus is on survivors,â€ she explained. â€œi want to help other people who are hiding out and feel like their voices are restricted. i really am so much stronger now, in so many ways.â€ â£
â€¢â£

text:
community challenge....show up! 
february 13th @ 6 pm, eau methodist church! 
iâ€™m a directly challenging all parents to attend this event and to bring your children! i am challenging all individuals to attend this event. 
the systemic issues are so much bigger than one individual & from changing our sexual assault policy at the local high school, our middle school currently being engaged in the fight, to young women & children missing on a weekly basis, the issues are pervasive, nuanced, & systemic. this is a free event that you can attend & hear from our ever growing list of experts, survivors, parents, students, teachers, & specialists that will be in attendance. do not think you or your family are immune from being impacted. 
itâ€™s often not the conversations we are having, but the ones we arenâ€™t that are the issue! letâ€™s learn how to combat these issues together, while eliminating the stigmas off talking about them. #muterkelly #metoo #muterkellychicago #believesurvivors #timesup

valentineâ€™s day seminar
jasmine johnson
thursday feb 14 from 11:00-12:30, hammer conference room
me too; now what? 
we've heard their stories, we've told our own but when and how does the healing begin?  jasmine, licensed clinical therapist,  provides an introduction to the journey to addressing and healing from all forms of sexual violence and violations.  this will jumpstart participants understanding and motivation to begin to work through the traumas associated with sexual harassment, rape, molestation, violence, and sexually inappropriate behaviors.  while the movement against those that violate has been a huge collective step, many are left with an open wound that affects them daily.  this seminar is designed to address and validate triggers, and offering coping mechanisms for sexual trauma; as well as for family, friends, and community allies wanting to provide support. 
jasmine johnson-decosta, the owner of blue pearl therapy llc, has been providing therapeutic services in a variety of settings for over 15 years. she has been fulfilled at helping clients work through challenging times and reach their goals. jasmine is a solution-focused therapist with an emphasis on a strength-based approach. her clients are able to identify their own strengths, resiliency, and resources to improve any situation causing distress. jasmine has extensive work with clients living with post traumatic stress disorder (ptsd), medical illness and injury counseling, military/civilian sexual trauma, veteran and caregiver related stressors. #metoo #jasminejohnson  @bluepearltherapyllc

text:
awesome clip from @anandwrites on @morningjoe about the problems of identity politics.

i couldn't fit all of the goodness, but here's some of what he said: "i think it is so fascinating that we are having a conversation about the problems of identity politics, at a table of five men.â€
[brief awkward banter, then he continued]
"there are excesses in every cultural wave. when you have a rightist cultural wave, thereâ€™s excesses, when you have a market philosophy that entrenches itself, thereâ€™s excesses as well as good things. and you may be right that there are excesses in the current wave of culture around identity. but i think... you canâ€™t start there. 
what is extraordinary that is happening in our time, the things i think you reflexively push back against, is a real awakening at the heart of american discourse, in the mainstream of american discourse, about experiences of what it has been like to be a woman, what it has been like to be black, what it has been like to be an immigrant, what it has been like to be a muslim... that weâ€™re actually not a part of the discourse.
i will tell you, as an indian american, born, growing up in this country, there were experiences i have gone through in my life that only now do i realize were absolutely because of how i look. and i didnâ€™t have that language 15 years ago when i was going through those things.
that language now exists." ... he goes on to talk about what he's learned from the #metoo movement. highly recommend the full clip.
(h/t for the find, @irincarmon!)

jilly cooper: #metoo is diminishing men

text: message from our friend and sister victoria obando, part of @cudjnicaragua and student of unan-rurd, to all our companions in the struggle and the nicaraguan people: the revolution will be transfeminist or it will not be! #lesvamosasacar #libertadya they take us out to the patio (sun) twice a week for only 25 minutes and when they return to the galley they strip us completely in front of all our companions, 103, exposing in front of all prisoners. this, forming a tremendous vulgarity, forcing us to do squats, an act that fills us with shame and indignation by having to expose our bodies in this degrading way. the same happens at the exit of the prison when they take us to the courts, in this case with the officers and their constant and offensive shouts "let's go huevones", "here there are only men who hang their testicles and penis." the same goes for the departure and entry of family and conjugal visits.  even so we do not give up and we remain rebellious and firm before all for the defense of our sexual identity. with love: victoria obando valverde  #freeallnicaprisoners #feminist #feminism #gay #lgbt #love #art #equality #lesbian #lgbtq #women #girlpower #bisexual #pride #feminismo #funny #transgender #loveislove #selflove #feminista #trans #woman #metoo #fortnite #girl #selfcare #womenempowerment

th, iâ€™m posting my personal picks for best six movies of 2018. ğŸğŸğŸğŸğŸğŸğŸğŸ my number one favorite movie of 2018 is a draw between on the basis of sex & the favourite:
on the basis of sex: a biographical drama based on the life & early cases of supreme court justice ruth bader 
ginsburg (rbg), with brilliant performances from british actress felicity jones, armie hammer, justin theroux, sam waterston & kathy bates. i found this movie to be both historically informative & incredibly inspirational. rbg 
has always been one of my living personal super heroes. she embodies the many traits one would aspire to achieve in a single life time; highly intelligent, classy, playful, as well as full of personal style & integrity. this movie 
captures rbgâ€™s remarkable, tenacious spirit in full bloom!
having said all that, sadly, this film has been overlooked throughout the awards this year due to the sheer quantity 
of high quality, magnificent performances & screenplays. nonetheless, a â€˜must seeâ€™ in my most humble opinionâ€¦!
ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ the favourite: poised to secure a place in oscar history, this dark comedic period piece based upon queen anneâ€™s reign 
in england features the complex, sometimes humorous relationship between a frail, failing queen anne & her feisty 
attendants. olivia colmanâ€™s portrayal of the hot-tempered, ailing queen anne added a hilarious new take on royal lifestyle
behind closed doors. the thorny relationship between abigail (emma stone) & lady sarah (rachel weisz) is complicated, 
forged from equal forces of sinister jealousy & endearing charm. overall, this film was entertaining & masterfully portrayed.

text: when i decided to leave jehovah witnesses, the religion of my birth to my adulthood.  there was many factors that i took into account for my recovery as person from a faith that was controlling.  one was how my immediate family would treat me.  once i realized that there love was based on conditions, it made it easier to let go of them.  do i get emotional at holliday time?  yes, but to know that it was not real love makes it easier. one thing i do know is who are my true friends and that i am truly grateful.  what they had taught me is to love my children for who they are and not what i want them to be. #ubu #religion #god #jesus #jehovahswitnesses #jehovahwitness #jehovah #jehovahwitnesses #lovequotes #love #raiseyourvibe #anxietyquotes #metoo #truth #parenting #parenthood #recovery #recoveryquotes #soberlife #overeatersanonymous #now #selfworth #jworganization #jworg

text:
yesterday, i went to the grand palace in bangkok. the intensity of the crowd was too much for my newly discovered empathic-introverted self. the people going in were shoving their way through, and once inside, quickly snapping photos in a kneeling temple poseÂ Â and then rushing their way back through the exits.
.
i can not help but wonder: what in the world are they looking for with that kind of desperation and did they find it? what if we sought after authenticity like we seek these inauthentic images to display to the world?
.
i refuse to spend my days curating an image that suggests my life is different from what it is. the reality is, so many of us are fighting uphill battles.Â Â so much of the pain many are in, is because weâ€™re being honest. unleashing your truth about your realities can feel like the most threatening thing in the world, but it can not/will not compare to the exuberant joy of knowing you are fully alive and aware of what is going on around you.
.
many wait until the depression is so bad, or divorce is on the way, or they are helpless, hopeless and out of options. when we are there, the temptation is to take that pain, and all the scary details with it, and rearrange the story. the best thing you can do:Â Â sit...with...your...truth.Â Â trust that it needs to be felt. your pain needs to be given aÂ Â voice, and once you begin this practice the fake external pursuits, will lose their power.
.
i have felt crazy most of my life. i was embarrassed by the way i interpreted my story. i felt i was too sensitive. i thought that anyone else would have survived my childhood better than i did. you know where those thoughts get me? to convincing myself that lying to myself and the world about all the important stuff is ok, because my truth was too much.
.
to every single one of you going through the trenches of life changing cycles, i want you to know that the work you are doing is one of the bravest things you can do.Â Â you are welcome here! and if you need to release some anger....break someones selfie stick. but, of course... apologize.
.
be well! i am fighting for each of you...
.

text:
someone asked me the other day to pick a product that i can't live without.  but that is hard because there are a lot of things that i use, but could live without if i had too.  so if i have to pick one, it would be my thieves cleaner.  it's an all purpose, plant based cleaner.  i used to have breathing problems when cleaning my house with harsh chemical cleaners.  my respiratory problems would prevent me from cleaning because i would feel light headed, even with the windows open.  i would start coughing and my breathing issues would increase.  i don't have any of these issues anymore.  thieves cleaner not only smells so good but it also boosts my immune system while i clean. 
it is also safe my my dogs.  research shows that pets are dying earlier and earlier and it's do to the chemicals that we expose them too.  these chemicals are also hormone disrupters in both children and adults.  so if i had to pick a product that i couldn't live without it would be my thieves cleaners because it not only cleans better than any other product i have tried on the market, it works with my body instead of against, and it cleans every surface.  itâ€™s the only cleaner we have under the sink. check out the science experiment our friends did. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
#holisticliving #wellness #wellnessinsideout #agouldstory #fgnaturalwellness #selfcare #wellnesswednesday #metoo #healthyliving #healthyhome #healthyfamilies #plantbasedlifestyle #plantsarelife

text:
welcome!!! so youâ€™ve been here for a while know a little about me but thought iâ€™d share a piece of me you may not know. .
.
.
i was born and raised in the bronx (yes just like @jlo ), by a single mom. i went to catholic schools from 7th grade all the way to college...yup! college too! my mom figured it out every step of the way...seriously i could cry; how do moms do that? i never knew when she was struggling. she sent my sister and i to puerto rico almost every summer for â€œvacationâ€ i had no clue it was to get us out of the our neighborhood. i truly feel like i wanted for nothing but i always wanted more! .
.
.
i donâ€™t mean it like she didnâ€™t do enough ~ i mean like she opened that door to opportunity, to desire and to experiences and an inner understanding that the world was bigger than our 5th story walk up! ya feel me? .
.
.
this past weekend i was able to see how so many of us can start anywhere and arrive anywhere we want. i was welcomed into someoneâ€™s dream home, i was welcomed into a network of women and long time friends that are all coming from some place and desiring more not just for themselves but their families and friends. .
.
.
so i welcome you into my space, my work and soon my dream home and invite you to think about how you have the choice to say yes to the invitation to walk through the door of your deepest desires and co-create the life you want ~ whatever that looks like for you!
.
.
.
you can go fast alone you can go far together! .
.
.

text:
egon schiele was not a sex offender

the 100th anniversary of austrian artistâ€™s death has arrived just in time for the #metoo movement

jane kallir
1st june 2018 13:11 gmt

egon schiele, liebesakt, studie (1915)Â leopold museum; vienna

the 100th anniversary of egon schieleâ€™s death has arrived just in time for the #metoo movement. commemorative exhibitions are taking place this year in moscow, boston, vienna, paris, london, liverpool and new york city, too, when the met breuer presents a show (3 july-7 october) on scofield thayer, the first us schiele collector. responding to the ongoing focus on sexual harassment, bostonâ€™s museum of fine arts saw fit to add wall labels addressing the artistâ€™s alleged mistreatment of women for its klimt and schiele exhibition (until 28 may). when the contemporary artist chuck close was accused of sexual harassment, the new york times gratuitously included schiele in its pantheon of historical artist-abusers. in the furore of our current moment, it is easy to forget that every allegation of abuse must be weighed according to its specific merits. schieleâ€™s relationships with women are difficult for us to judge, not only because no living witnesses survive, but also because present-day standards are so very different from those that prevailed in early 20th-century austria.
the specific allegations centre on three aspects of his life and work: his arrest for â€œpublic immoralityâ€ in 1912, his treatment of the various women in his life and the erotic nature of his drawings. in each case, however, the allegations are not justified by the facts.
the so-called prison incident took place when schiele was living with his model and lover, wally neuzil, in the rural town of neulengbach. the â€œincidentâ€ was precipitated by a teenage runaway, who asked the couple to take her to her grandmother in vienna. once in the city, the girl got cold feet, and the three returned to neulengbach a day later. by then, however, the teenagerâ€™s father had filed charges of kidnapping and statutory rape, which led the police to conduct a thorough investigation of the artist. in the course of that investigation, a third charge was levelled against schiele: t

text:
i've always liked freaky friday. also, the boy version with judge reinhold. i always wanted it to be way freakier, though. switching bodies with someone you love isn't just a chance to learn a lesson, it's a chance to get away with some deeply fucked up shit.
â™¾
ground rules: i'm not switching with a kid, that's just wrong. don't mess with kid's lives. have some respect.
â™¾
now that we've established freaky friday only happens between cosenting adults, let's admit that the very first thing to do is sex stuff; don't even care who it is. i've only known sex as me and the chance to do it in someone else's body is so singularly unique that i'm not missing it just because it's "morally reprehensible."
â™¾
wait, i'm going about this wrong: get specific. if i were to freaky friday with anyone, obviously it'd be @spn.cr and not just because that means right now i'd be shaping and diversifying the conversation around how storytellers impact culture and change in park city, utah. it's also because he's the only person i know who would ever go along with this - and consent matters people.
â™¾
so, what would i do in his body? also, hi babe i love and miss you and hope you're having the most fun! first, i'd dress him in ridiculous russian dj clothes. after that, i'd probably fuck with his friends. my first thought would be to call @ashleydemoff but she'd clock it in two seconds and then insist we go get spencer's body wasted, which would totally be fun, but.
â™¾
what i'd really do is call up @sinagrace. sina's the kind of person who can appear overly credulous but that's just because he's seen some things and believes in a world where anything is possible, so why not? btw - keep those people.
â™¾
anyhow, i'd tell him that i've finally decided to marry japhy and have devised the perfect way to propose: he always said he's wanted to go skydiving so we do that (i know! love is a whole thing!), but at the top i'll throw japhy out sans parachute, follow after him, catch him, rescue him. once we land, i whisper in his ear, "i wanted to prove i'll always be there to rescue you" and then pull out a ring. freaky, right? â™¾
- diary of a #sundance widow, week two

text: this pic is from the movie mandy (2018). 3 years ago today i learned what ken ward did to my fv.  while she remembers the hurt and angry look on my face as she told me everything, i remember the zombie-like fashion in which she described everything. our lives have been deeply affected by what ken ward did, but fortunately our love and stubbornness have allowed us to continue fighting for her recovery and any form of justice. in good news, this month she has started some serious recovery methods and theyâ€™re working; more on that in one of the next posts. so, last month was the worst she has been since the few months after everything happened. it was bad, and her emotional and mental stability were severely erratic and dark. but, late in the month, we sat down and watched mandy and it was in the scene depicted above that everything changed. i cried because i could relate to his emotions but have not been able to release anything because life keeps going and i have to be there for fv. fv cried  because this scene gave her an idea of what i have been feeling. and from that moment has began an amazing effort at working on her recovery and it is already showing. i am so grateful, and am so proud of her. sometimes a positive change can be triggered by the most unexpected things, like this crazy movie.  right now, we are both being positive and working on her getting better.  hard to believe that an asshole with a limp dick could cause all the pain we have gone through and that the @irvinepolice didnâ€™t even bother to question him. more posts coming. #coercionisnotconsent #limpdickrapist #mandymovie #metoo #kennethward #corestrategycorp #futureforms #lds #saddlebackirvine #woodbridgeirvine #irvineldsstake

text:
i am going to be posting a bit less as i recover from the surgery i had yesterday. 
after all my weight loss i still could not fit into any cute tops or workout bras because of my large chest so decided to go for a reduction and lift!! i am heading back to the doctor this morning to see the results!! i can't wait to see how much was reduced and have a total transformation body!! ğŸ‘™

the best part of the entire thing was being sober and debt free as a result of my hard work over the past two years. i will be 2 years sober next week and truly living my best life, the life i visualized for myself in treatment and used to believe was impossible. 
don't let alcohol and debt hold you back from your dreams. it all starts with awareness of the issue and connecting the dots between alcohol, health and wealth.

text:
ğŸ“£today is let's talk day by bell to raise awareness about mental health. ğŸ“£.. .

it a day that you start to realize that you aren't the only one struggling or have struggled. ğŸ¤”.. .

it seems only yesterday that i was diagnosed with bpd, anxiety, and panic disorder. ğŸ‘©â€âš•ï¸.. .

on one hand i felt a sense of relief. but i also felt a sense of failure. ğŸ™ğŸ¤¦.. .

i kept my feelings and thoughts to myself ğŸ™Šfor many years. i was determined to be a police officer ğŸ‘® and i couldn't risk anyone knowing. .

i also felt if i would be diagnosed with something i would be labeled, and people would look at me in a different light ğŸ’¡.. .

it's is so frustrating when you are legitimately upset about something and people don't take you seriously âŒ because that's my "condition" . .

or the opposite when you are having a hard time people just expect you to handle it in the same manner as they do. when you don't they get frustrated and often get angry ğŸ˜ .. .

whether you have a formal diagnosis, or just struggle ğŸ¤¦ with anxiety, depression and panic attacks. it is ok. .

first off, your surely not alone. ğŸ™‹.. . âŒsecondly you are within every right to have a shitty day. you are allowed to have bad days. âŒ.. . âœ”ï¸you are allowed to get upset.
âœ”ï¸you are allowed to show your emotions
âœ”ï¸you are allowed to experience your own feelings. . ğŸ‘‰it's ok if you have a melt down. . ğŸ‘‰it's ok if you yell. . ğŸ‘‰it's ok if you cry. .

it's ok if you feel like you just want to run away ğŸƒâ€â™€ï¸ from it all. .

that is all normal ğŸ‘Œ.. .

so the special shout out ğŸ“¢ to the mom that who has had the melt down, the tears ğŸ˜¢, the fears, the sadness â˜¹ï¸, the guilt. .

today and every day is your day. .

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
gop is dead. gop remains dead. and we have killed him. how shall we comfort ourselves, the murderers of all murderers? what was holiest and mightiest of all that the world has yet owned has bled to death under our knives: who will wipe this blood off us? what water is there for us to clean ourselves? what festivals of atonement, what sacred games shall we have to invent? is not the greatness of this deed too great for us? must we ourselves not become gods simply to appear worthy of it?

howlindsey doody

text:
you deserve to be happy! you have the right to live a fulfilling life that brings you every possible opportunity for growth, exploration, and love. in growth you learn pain and hardship. in exploration you find things that you become passionate about and things that you fight against. love gives you powerful connections to people and those things around you, but it teaches you patience and a way to display your boundaries to the world around you. all of these things help add meaning to our lives, but if not done correctly, all of these things can be detrimental. learn the laws of love. what it is and what it isn't. be invested in your growth. note those things that are taking from you and those things that are giving. explore with an open mind but pay close attention to your energy. get to know who you are and who you aren't. and while traveling these paths, try your hardest to do so genuinely. don't let the limitations of society tell you how to grow, explore, or love! life is not a one size fit all. there is no one way for everyone to live. .

â€œwhat is happening to me happens to all fruits that grow ripe. it is the honey in my veins that makes my blood thicker, and my soul quieter.â€ â€•friedrich nietzsche
-----------------------
hello to all the new members of our tribe. my name is ayesha ophelia and 7 years or more ago the girlfriend manifesto came precociously bounding into the world. my desire was to share some of the wisdom of being a life longer seeker, dreamer, and wild woman.
ã€°
my personal manifesto consisted of a strong belief in the healing bonds between women, a spirit of seeing that adventure is ours for the taking and often holds keys to doors you didn't even know you want to open but are so worth while, a radical unwavering self love practice through the stages and phases of a women's journey, and the quest to understand the mystery of life through spiritual practice.
ã€°
the creation of my manifesto has lead me to discovering more of my personal power and this community is a reflection of how much potential we all contain!
ã€°
all are welcome! respect and loving solution based thinking are really all i ask in this space. are we going to complain about the old or create the new? also i don't buy into the us against them approach. you can't solve a problem with the same energy that created it! i never shoot the messenger, i don't avoid triggers, and heartful compassion is the basis of all we do around here.
ã€°
so welcome! meet me in the comments and share your one word affirmation for the day! mine is moist...cause moisture is life! â¤ï¸ğŸ’‹

text:
ğŸ’™its bell lets talk day. a day where our social media feeds are filles with real stories from our friends and family who have experienced personally or professionally the realities of mental illness and the importance of discussing mental health. .
.
ive been very outspoken on my social media channels about my personal experiences with depression, anxiety and ptsd ( and less known dissasociative disorder) from childhood and youth. i was sexually abused at a child at a camping trip i went on without my family. then as a young adolescent i was groomed online and sexually assaulted by an older man in the parking lot of a community center. he gave me $200 and i took my friend to mcdonalds and bought 5 or 10 magazines.. i can still remember to this day the smell of the fries and the sickness i felt in my stomach.
.
.
some of my battles have been fought on my own through coping mechanisms such as alcohol. or isolating myself. letting my depression keep me in my bed for days at a time. my anxiety riddling me with beliefs that im not worthy of the love i have or the beautiful family ive built. that im not worthy of happiness. .
.
.ultimately it was the countless hours of therapy and counselling that helped me identify the roots of my pain, my triggers (working with victims of crime and sexual abuse was clearly one of them), and to identify healthier strategies to cope when i felt an episode coming on.
.
thankfully i was fortunate enough to work for an employer that offers employee and family assistance programs. those therpists i saw...not once or twice but countless times over the course of 10 years have helped me in so many ways. they gave me the courage to speak out and open up about my struggle and help heal. i will likely always live with some remanence of my afflictions but i open up and share them now with the hopes that i can also help someone else seek help and not feel ashamed or embarrsed because all of us, no matter what, or who we are, have our own struggles.ğŸ’™
.

i challenge you today to also open up and share your lets talk story.ğŸ’“
.
.
.
#endthestigma #mentalhealth #bellletstalk #letstalkday #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #bellletstalkday #survivor

text:
sex trafficking is a booming industry. we cannot talk about it enough because so many kids are being impacted. the youngest child rescued in this sting was 6 years old. yes, 6! take note of the fact that these girls were solicited online in chat rooms because we  are constantly pushing internet safety. we also want you to take note of the fact that these victims are often sold from one pimp to another, which is how the trucking aspect of the conversation comes into play. these are just a few examples of a global crisis that has surpassed drug trafficking in revenue generation. we need those in our local communities to take the time to learn the signs to spot a possible sex trafficking victim and then be willing to call for help on behalf of the victim. this is everyone's problem and it will take everyone caring enough to help in order to end this epidemic. if you are a victim or suspect that a child may be a victim of human trafficking, please call 911 or call the national human trafficking resource center at 1-888-373-7888 for help. all victims of slavery and human trafficking have rights and are protected by international, federal, and state law. 
the hotline is:â€¨(1) anonymous and confidential;â€¨(2) available 24 hours a day, seven days a week;â€¨(3) able to provide help, referral to services, training, and general information; (4) accessible in 170 languages;â€¨(5) operated by a nonprofit, nongovernmental organization; andâ€¨(6) toll free. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist  #super bowl

save bracelet
every bracelet purchased contributes to domestic violence prevention.
together we can raise awareness to put an end to abusive relationships.

donations
we strive to help abusive relationships by sending money to domestic violence prevention organizations across usa and worldwide. our mission is supporting someone who keeps returning to an abusive relationship together. domestic violence, sexual violence, stalking, and intimate partner violence are major public health problems in the united states and worldwide. our understanding of these forms of violence has grown substantially over the years. 
one in four women will experience severe physical violence by an intimate partner in their lifetime. one in five women (and 1 in 71 men) in the united states have been raped at some time in their lives. every bracelet set purchased helps raise money towards such an ongoing increasing violence in today's world. together we can all love again.ğŸ’œ come take a look at all the styles and colors you can choose to help raise awareness in finding solutions for preventing domestic violence

text:
today is #bellletstalkday and it's that time of year i share my story and help raise awareness.
this is the face of someone suicidal. i mean hidden behind all the smiles on instagram is as well. but being suicidal doesn't always look like what people expect.
i am diagnosed with ptsd, anxiety and depression. i am currently undergoing semantic therapy for a sexual assault that happened to me almost 4 years ago...
i had an alcohol dependency and an eating disorder. 
i cut myself on a daily basis in hopes that feeling pain was better than feeling nothing...
but i was wrong. i wasnt as alone as i felt.
i still have my ups and downs, every day is a battle in my mind on if i'm worth the effort. but i'm slowly learning my worth.
these past few months i've made a lot of changes bettering myself, i've had a lot of self discovery, and i've grown more than i thought i ever could.
every day isnt a battle with my life. i mean i still have those days but not as much. i still have nightmares but i've become better with coping. i no longer use drugs and alcohol to take away the pain. 
i cant even describe in words the battle i've been fighting since i was 17, but i hope this helps.
i finally see my self worth, and someday i hope you can see yours too ğŸ’•
be kind everyone, and let's help end the stigma!
#bellletstalk2019 #mentalillness #mentalhealthawareness #ptsd #survivor #metoo #endthestigma #anxiety #depression #suicidal #raiseawareness

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
#metoo in south korea: court lengthens jail term for former speed skating coach in sexual abuse case
#
seoul: a south korean appeals court on wednesday nearly doubled jail time for a former speed skating coach convicted of hitting a two-time olympic champion, citing a need to warn sports officials against the use of violence as a training tool. women attend a protest as a part of the #metoo movement on international women's day in seoul, south korea. reuters the case, and the athleteâ€™s accusation that the coach had also sexually abused her, has triggered south koreaâ€™s largest investigation into physical and sexual assaults in sport after the events sparked a flood of similar accusations. speed skating has a huge and devoted following in south korea, which has won 24 gold medals in the sport since it became an olympic event in 1992, more than any other country. in september, a lower court had jailed the former national coach, cho jae-beom, for 10 months on a conviction of assaulting olympic champion shim suk-hee, 21. â€œthe defendant...has shown regret but has severely hit the victim with his fists and feet ever since the victim was young, taking as the reason a slack attitude during training,â€ the suwon district court said as it raised the term to 18 months. â€œtheâ€¦

text:
this may be a taboo topic, but f**k it - thats what this is about. i canâ€™t speak for anyone else but, through my own experiences iâ€™ve sometimes faced inequality and judgement in the workplace from other women. with the uprise of the #metoo movement, i couldnâ€™t help but notice that no one was really talking about the women who think they need to act like men in order to further their own careers. iâ€™ve experienced this first hand, coming into interviews, watching women scan me up and down and make preliminary decisions on who i am before even giving me an opportunity to open my mouth. â£
â£
women who feel they need to make a power play in order to keep you where you are so that you come nowhere near stepping on their territory. we forget that youâ€™re only as successful as your weakest link, and i truly believe that in all aspects of life, not just in work. â£
â£
so rather than trying to protect what youâ€™ve got, and your own progression, try to step outside of yourself and help someone else be better. in turn iâ€™m sure youâ€™ll find youâ€™ll be rewarded and grow from the experience too. â£
â£
have you ever experienced this in the work place? share your story below. â£
â£
